{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657463/1924012801/0707.xml":{"full_text":"EXPANSION IS SEEN\nIN STEEL INDUSTRY\nMaterial for Millions of New\nAutos Expected to Be\nBiggest 1924 Factor.\n11V J. C. ROVLK.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nXEW YORK, January 28. \u2014Strong\nhopes exist among steel producers\nthat mill operations will increase\nmaterially in the next two or three\nmonths. The year, they say. is too\nyoung to warrant definite predictions\nand January is a poor month on\nwhich to base trend predictions in\ncomparison with March and October,\nthe pivotal periods. Still they re\ngard the outlook for increased pro\nduction as favorable.\nThe fact that modernization of the\nHomestead works of the Carnegie\nSteel Company will be begun shortly\nsupports tliis viewpoint. Homer D.\nWilliams, president of the company,\ntoday confirmed reports that large\nsums would be spent in rehabilitat\ning the plant.\nMillions in Plant Expansion.\n\u2022\u2019Heports that $20,000,000 would be\npent on the work are somewhat\nexaggerated.\" he added. \u201cIt is hardly\nknown yet what amount will be re\nquired. The object of the work is\nalong the lines ot making possible a\ngreater output with less men. but it\nis by no means certain that there will\nfie an appreciable out in the number\nof unskilled workers employed at\nHomestead.\" Mr. Williams said.\n\u201cThe new equipment, of course, will\nbe labor-saving equipment.\" be ex\nplained. \u201cHut there is a likelihood\nthat tile capacity of the plant will be\ngreatly increased, and it may be\ni hat more men will have to be em\nployed than are now on the pay roll\nto care for the new rate of output.\u201d\nThe work at Homestead is along the\nlines of reducing fixed charges and\ncutting costs, which is making so\nnoticeable an appearance in many\nlines of manufacture.\nI.OUfr Production fonts Sought.\nBars, plates and shapes, the heavy\nrolled products which were under\nparticular scrutiny late last year as\nto price maintenance, now are in fair\nshape, according to the orders on the\nmill books. There is a fair movement\nof bars to cold finished manufactur\ners on contracts and jobbers are buy\ning liars rather freely. This latter\ntendency has been strengthened by\nthe possibility of a suspension in the\nbituminous coal fields next spring,\nand jobbers are stocking early for the\nspring trade. Some of the plate mills\nare running at high schedules, while\nothers are closed entirely, but the ex\ncess of plate rolling capacity pro\nduced by the war is not proving so\nburdensome as was feared.\nThe automobile industry is consum\ning large quantities of material, and\nindications are that It will continue\nto do so. The Ford production\nschedule has been advanced to 8,200\nears and trucks a dav, and is ex\npected to reach the 10,000 mark April\n1, The company is well supplied\nwith materials, and reports from\ndealers indicate the spring demand\nwill be fully up to expectations.\nAuto Finns Heavy Buyers.\nThe Ford Company, however, is not\nthe only- maker sharing increased\nbusiness. One of the largest parts\nmakers, who does business with near-\nIv every Detroit automobile manu\nfacturer. declared today his schedules\nfor January were double those of\nlast year. Kvery one of his old j\ncustomers lias increased orders, and\nmany new customers have been added, i\nGeneral Motors probably- will turn I\nout at least 730.000 cars and the Over- I\nland Company 300.000. Added to this\ncomes the report from Dodge Broth- I\ners that unfilled orders for Janu\nary are greater than those of last\nJanuary by 25 per cent. Dodge\nBrothers last year produced 180,000\nvehicles, but their schedule for this\nyear is 225,000. This is significant,\nfor in previous years the Dodge\nBrothers\u2019 business has been an accu\nrate barometer of business for the\nIndustry as a whole.\n4,000,000 far* Predicted.\nThe concensus of opinion anjong\nmanufacturers is there will be more\nthan 4.000.000 cars sold in 1924 If\nbusiness in the last half of the year\nis not affected by the presidential\nelection bogey. A slignt recession is\nexpected to .begin in July and last\nthrough October, but this has been\ntaken account of in the 4.000.000-ear\nsales estimate.\nCOMMODITY MEWS\nWIRED STAR FROM\nEMTIRE COUNTRY\nXEW ORLKAXS, January 2S.\u2014Mil\n1* rs have bought practically all the\nLouisiana rice crop, [laying $4.90 a\nbarrel for some of the late purchases.\nThis means they must get s*i cents\na pound for the best grades to come\nout.\nHOUSTON', January 28. \u2014Business in\nthe oil towns of the gulf coast fields\nlias been stimulated by the advance\nannounced last week liy the Humble\noil and Refining Company in gulf\ncoast crude to $1.65 a barrel for A\ngrade and $1.40 for B grade.\n4JIATTLE, January 28. \u2014Retail dry\nand millinery lines are active\nbeJV>and the larger stores already\nare in the market for summer and\nTall stocks. The largest department\nsi ore here will send a staff of buy\ners to Europe next month to place in\nEngland. Germany, France, Italy and\n\u2022Spain orders outlined on the belief\ni bat the turnover in 1924 will be\nfully equal to that of last year.\nKANSAS CITY, January 28.\u2014Build\ning operations will increase this\nspring, according to many lumber\nmen who attended the Southwestern\nlumbermen's Association convention\nhere. D. J. Farr, president of the as\nsociation predicted a steady increase\nin sales without danger of inflation.\nSAX FRANCISCO? January 28.\nShipping companies here report that\nthe movement of California canned\ndried fruit to Europe will continue\nfor some time to come. Cargo space\non European-bound boats has been\nContracted for well into April.\nDETROIT. January 28.\u2014The fact\nthat the Paige Detroit Motor Com\npany plans to go in for volume pro\nduction this year, turning out about\n75,000 cars, is held responsible for\nthe drastic price-cut recently an\nnounced. which reduced the price of\nthe touring car model $605.\nCLEVELAND. January 28.\u2014Auto\nmobile dealers and manufacturers\nhere expect another prosperous year.\n10. S. Jordan, president of the Jordan\nMotor Company, declared he antici\npated strong demand this veal- from\nthose sections which have been most\nbackward in recovering from the\npost-war slump.\nST. LOUIS. January 28. \u2014Failure of\nthe demand for government sealskins\nwas attributed to the desire of Amer\nican women to have a new fur coat\nach year by Phillip B. Fouke of the\nT'ouke Fur Company, in a report to\na committee representing the Secre\ntary of Commerce. He said sealskins\nwore well for three or four years.\nPARIS MARKET HEAVY.\nPARIS, January 28.\u2014Prices were\nheavy on the bourse today. Three\nper cent rentes 54 francs.\nExchange on London, 92 francs 20\ncentimes.\nFive per cent loan, 71 francs 30\ncentimes.\nThe dollar was quoted at, 21 francs\n72 centimes.\nFINANCIAE.\nNEW YORK CURB MARKET\nRecrind by Private Wire Direct te The Star Ol\u00dfce\nIIV WILLIAM K. HEFFKRXAN.\nNEW YORK, January 28.\u2014Th%start\nof the new week on the Curb Market\nwas another day of advancing prices,\nalthough the rise was not as uniform\nas that of last week.\nProfit-taking sales became increas\ningly heavy In soma directions, re\nsulting in good sized declines from\ntop prices in a few- specialty favor\nites. Included among these was the\nnew Warner Brothers Pictures, which\nsold down to 10, against the previous\nclose of 11%. These shares were\nbrought on the market for the first\ntime last week, initial sales taking\nplace between 12 and 1244.\nNet earnings for the nine months\nended December 31 last, after all\ndeductions, were $685,780. It was re\nported that the management intends\nto place the stock on an annual divl-\nXEW YORK, January 28.\u2014 Following\nis an official list of bonds and stocks\ntraded In on the New York Curb Mar\nket today:\nSalon In BONDS',\nthousand*. Illtfh. Low.\n4 Allied Barkers tis.. 70*4