Silver 01 1 .8!\n3So Am Gold A P. 3% 5% 5.*,\n500 Spearhead Gold .95 I .95\nGO Stewart Mine, .92 .I*2 .92\n6 Tonopah Extens I}J I}J\n7 United Eastern .81* .80 .88\n1 T\u2019nlted Verde Ext.. 27 27 27\n20 U S Conti new wi.. .20 .20 .20\n15 Unify Gold I'% If, 1%\n7 Wenden Copper 1* 4 I*4 1%\n30 West End Consol... .65 .65 .85\nGROUND IS BROKEN\nFOR COLORED SCHOOL\nWork Soon to Begin on Cardinal\nGibbons Institute, St. Marys\nCounty, Md.\nWork shortly will begin on the\nerection of a school for colored youth\nin St. Marys county. Md., to be\nknown as the Cardinal Gibbons In\nstitute, ground for which was broken\nFriday.\nThe first sod was turned by Ed\nward Colbert, colored, of this city,\nwho made the first cash donation to\nthe fund. Chairmen of the various\ncolored committees representing\ncounties in Maryland each removed\na shovelful of earth and pledged\nfunds.\nAddresses were made by Admiral\nWilliam S. Benson, I*. S. N.. retired;\nWilliam S. Aumeu of Baltimore, past\nstate deputy of the Knights of Co\nlumbus and vice president of the\nboard of trustees of the institute;\nL. I\u2019. Williams of Wynne. Md., a\nmember of the Maryland house of\ndelegates and treasurer of the board\nof trustees; A. C. Monahan, secretary\nof the board of trustees; Prof.\nThomas Turner of Howard Univer\nsity. president of the Federated Col\nored Catholics of the United States.\nThe opening prayer was by Rev.\nJohn La Farge, S. J.. of Ridge, Md..\nand the closing prayer by Rev. James\nB. Matthews. S. J., of Bel Alton.\nMd., both members of the board of\ntrustees. Rev. Hugh A. Dalton, rec\ntor at Leonardtown, Md.. and Rev.\nH. J. Parker, S. J., pastor of the\ncolored church adjacent to the school,\nalso took part in the exercises. The\nchildren of St Peter Clavier School\nsang several hymns ami patriotic\nsongs during the services.\nFoundations of ornithology were\nlaid by two Englishmen- in the sev\nenteenth century,\nANOTHER TEXTILE\nMERGERREPORTED\nNew England Mills to Take\nOver Large Indian Head\ni\nPlant in Alabama.\n_\nj Special Dispatch to The Star,\ni BOSTON. January 28. In line with\nj the tendency of New England textile\nI mills to broaden activities in the\nsouth, come announcements that the\nNashua Manufacturing Company will\nmerge with the Indian Head mills of\nAlabama and that the Lonsdale Com\npany of Providence contemplates en\nlarging its plant at Seneca, S. C.\nThe Nashua company has had a\nclose working agreement with the\nIndian Head mills for some time. It\nis planned to use the Alabama plant\nas a feeder to the New Hampshire\nunits, making, there products which\ncan bo more advantageously turned\nout in the south.\nThe Lonsdale improvements call\nfor a weave shed for 1.000 looms and\ntransfer of 500 looms from Rhode Is\nland. This transfer may be held up,\nhowever, if the forty-eight-hour bill\nnow before the Rhode Island legis\nlature fails of passage.\n>inkr 10.152 Hnnk l.onna in Year.\nNEAV ORLEANS, January 28 (Spe\n-1 lai).\u2014Luring the past (rear the Fed\n-1 VT a,m Doan Bank here has made\nlO.lak loans totaling $21,938,000. Os\nj his ,suiii $5,94 9,000 went to farmers\ni 11 na *M22.000 to Alabama\na I-' d u \u2022\u00b0I\u201d )00 to Mississippi. Loans\ni l\u2019\u201e\u201e since its organization\ni total $76,225,009.\nItnilmndN Deport Good Gains.\n,r., S T\\ PAI1 January 38 (Special!.\u2014\nThe business situation in the north\nwest is accurately shown in the an\nnual statement issued today lie the\nGreat Northen and Northern Pacific\nrailroads, according to business men\nlu-re. hot- the last twelve months the\ngross income of the Great Northern\nincreased $16.624. 534, to $210,077,771\nas compared with 1922. The state\nment of the Northern Pacific showed\nmonths\u2019 gross revenue, $102,-\n99_,9ti9. an increase of $3,925.993\u25a0 op\nerating expenses, $80,364,819, an in\ncrease of 10.100: net operating in\nsl*-H)0.357, a decrease of $2,-\nJ 4 9,9a6.\nDetroit Auto IManta Booming,\nDETROIT, January 28 (Special).\u2014\nI-leight traffic on the Per*- Marquette\nrailroad in tills industrial section\nbelow tile levels of January,\nhut is steadily picking up.\nThe employment report for the last\nweek shows 257,813 workers, the higli\njest total ever reached in the city's\nhistory. Inasmuch as most of the\nj workers are employed in automobile\nfactories it proves the motor industry\n;is going ahead full speed. A year\njago tlte total employment was 194.-\n697.\nGasoline I\u2019ril-ps Jump.\nj DENVER. January 28 (Special).\u2014\niWith Salt Creek crude bringing s!,*\u2019(*\nja barrel or practh ally double the\n(I rice of a month ago. the filling\nstation price of gasoline here has\njumped from IT to 21 cents a gallon,\nand further increases are expected.\nFew cars have been stored because\njof the open winter, and the demand\nj for gas has declined only slightly.\nTolmic-ci> Market Active,\ni LYNCHBURG. Va.. January -_*4\ni (Spec ial ).\u2014Sales of dark loose-leaf\ntohaeco for the season on the local\n[open market were pressing 3.099.000\npounds today. The market\u2018continues\n\u25a0active. Last week\u2019s sales exceeded\n,509.090 pounds, and the price aver\nag( d $19.68.\nTANK WAGON PRICE\ni' OF GASOLINE RAISED\ni\n\nj One and Two Cent Advances In\nelude This City. Maryland. Vir\nginia and West Virginia.\nJ By flic Associated Press,\nj NEW YORK. January 28.\u2014Advances\nof I and 2 cents a gallon in the tank\nj wagon price of gasoline were put\ninto effect generally in states along\ntl.e Atlantic seaboard today. In\ncreases announced by the Standard\n(Oil Company of New Jersey brought\nthe price to 19 cents a gallon in\nj Maryland. Virginia and West Vir\nj ginia. and 19% cents in New Jersey\n1 and District of Columbia, exclusive\nol taxes. The Atlantic Refining\ni Company raised the price 2 cents to\n[l9 cents a gallon in Pennsylvania and\nDelaware.\nI The Texas Company met the in\n-1 crease throughout its territory.\nFOREIGN EXCHANGES\nIN'SHARP ADVANCE\n\nj Prospects of British Railway Strike\nSettlement Cause Sudden\nUpturns.\n1\nj By the Associated Press.\nI NEW YORK, January 2S.\u2014lmproved\nj prospects for the settlement of the\nBritish railway strike contributed to\na sharp rise in sterling exchange to\n-1 day, the demand rate mounting 2*4\ncents to $4.25%. The franc at the\nsame time gained 10 points at 4.61*4\nj cents as measures designed to sus\nj tain Paris exchange came to a test\nvote in the chamber of deputies.\nOther exchanges, with the exception\nI of Denmark, advanced in sympathy.\nI BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nSTEADILY IMPROVING\nI m\nPrice Trend and Flow of Goods to\nConsumers Reported\nSatisfactory.\ni Special Dispatch to The Star.\nI NEW YORK. January 2S. \u2014Events at\nj the turn of the year have further forti\nj fled confidence (n the business outlook,\nstates the Guaranty Survey, published\ntoday by the Guaranty Trust Company\nof New York.\n\"Buying is still generally conserva\ntive,\u201d the Survey continues. \u201cAs de\nliveries to distributors are relatively\nprompt and speculation for a rise In\ncommodity prices is not general, con\nditions in' mist branches of business do\nnot call for heavy inventory accumu\nlations. Nevertheless, activity in some\nlines is exceeding most expectations.\n\"The degree of confidence with which\nbusiness men make commitments de\npends largely upon two elements\u2014the\nrecent trend of prices and the factors\nwhich have affected their general aver\nage. and the evenness in the flow of\n1 goods from producers to consumers. To\nday these two factors promise a period\nI of generally stable business in the im-\nI mediate future.\nI \u201cThe most significant feature of re\ni*cnt prices in this country is the com\nparative steadiness of their average, de\nj spite a slight net decline in 1923. as\nJ compared with a more pronounced In\nI crease In the preceding year.\"\nConstables Get Half\nOs Bootleg Fines In\nPrince Georges Warfare\nSpeelnl Dispatch to The star.\nUPPER MARLBORO, Md.. Jan\nuary 28.\u2014Hoping to give Impetus\nto the fight against bootlegging\nin Prince Georges county, the\ncounty commissioners have passed\nan order allowing constables one\nhalf the fines Imposed by justices\nof the peace In liquor cases, un\nder the state law, where the in\nformation leading to conviction is\nfurnished by the constable.\nThis added allowance, it is\nhoped, will result In added activ\nity on the part of constables in\nliquor cases.\nBRANCHES REFUSED\nTO NATIONAL BANKS\nBY SUPREME COURT\n(Continued from First Page.)\nbanks at the Chicago and St. Louis\nexpositions and also that government\nagencies had adopted similar policies,\n\"with substantial uniformity.\" The\nDepartment of Justice\u2019s opinion May\n11, 1911, was referred to in this con\nnection.\nTo the contention that branch\nbanks were incidental necessities of\nbanking, Justice Sutherland said:\n\"The mere multiplication of places\nwhere the powers of a bank may be\nexercised is not, in our opinion, a\nnecessary incident of a banking busi\nness. It is wholly illogical to say\nthat a power which by fair construc\ntion of the statutes is found to be\ndenied nevertheless exists as an in\ncidental power.\n\"Clearly the state statute, by pro\nhibiting branches, does not frustrate\nthe purpose for which the bank was\ncreated or interfere with the dis\ncharge of its duties to the govern\nment or impair Its efficiency as a\nfederal agency.\nExisted Half Century,\nNational banking associations have\ngone on for more than half a cen\ntury without branches and upon the\ntheory of an absence of authority to\nestablish them.\nif the non-existence of such\nbranches or the absence of power to\ncreate them has operated or is cal\nculated to operate to the detriment\nof the government, or In such man\nner as to interfere with the efficiency\nof such associations as federal agen\ncies. or to frustrate their jmrposes.\nit is inconceivable that the fact would\nnot long since have been discovered\nand steps taken by Congress to\nremedy the omission.\n\"The state statute as applied to\n(national banks is. therefore. valid\n(and the corrollary that it is obliga\njtory and enforceable necessarily re\nsults, unless some controlling reason\n(forbids; and since the sanction lie- I\n(hind it is that of the state and not\n'that of the national government the\n(power of enforcement must rest with\njvhe former and not with the latter.\"\nJustice Sutherland added that the\n(state was \"neither seeking to en- 1\nforce a law of the United States nor I\nendeavoring to call the hank to ac- i\n\u2018count for an act in excess of its j\n(charter powers.\u201d I\nJustice Van d>- Vanter said that i\nI the dissenting justices thought that\nj national banks were not subject to\nstate laws in matters relating to the\nI corporate powers of such banks. The]\nJ control of states over national hanks. 1\ni h<- said, was confined exclusively to i\nI the dally obligations of the national j\nI banks \u00abuch as receipt of deposits and\npavment of checks.\nMissouri bad no authority to have i\nacted, he said, hut that only the\nj X'nited States could proceed in the\nj courts in such actions against the\nnational banks\nLlTret In I npltal.\nThe decision of Justice Slither-\nI land will not fn any way affect the\n1 local banking situation, it was tie\neland at the offices of controller of\nI the currency.\nUnlike states, where banks are\n1 governed bv state banking laws, the\ni District banking situation is rupei\ni viced bv the controller of the cur\ni r t rc authority for this supervision\nbeing vested in him through the\nMillspaugli bill, passed about eighteen\nmonths ago. He. therefore, can. at\nj his discretion, allow or- refuse per-\nI mission ft operate branches at will.\nBranch banking opponents in\nWashington, however, deejared this\n1 morning that if local branches are\nallowed to remain, steps will be\n1 taken leading to the annulment of\nI former Controller Crisslnger\u2019s acts in\nestablishing these branches, on the\ni ground that they are Illegal and a\nj violation of the intent of the Mills\npaugli bill.\nAppeal by flank.\nThe legality of the recent prac\ntice of some national banks in estab\nlishing branches was brought before\nthe Supreme Court in an appeal by\nthe First National Hank in St. Louis\nj to have set aside the decision of the\nMissouri courts holding that national\ni banks were subject to the branch\nbanking laws of the states.\nEighteen states\u2014Arkansas. Con\nnecticut, Illinois. Indiana. lowa. Kan\ni sas, Kentucky. Minnesota. Nebraska.\nNorth Dakota. New Mexico. Okla\ni horaa, Soutli Dakota. Utah. Washing\nton. West Virginia. \u2019Wisconsin and\nj Wyoming\u2014joined Missouri in assert\ning state control over national as\ni well as state and private banks in\n1 matters of such vital importance as\nI the establishment of branches. After\n|the case had been once argued and\nhad been set for reargument the fed\n-1 eral government was permitted to in-\nI tervene, and supported the St. Louis\nI anil a number of other national banks\nin the contention that states bad no\njurisdiction over matters controlled\nj by the national banking laws.\nAttack on Practice.\nDeclaring branch banking destruc\ntive. centralizing and monopolistic,\nthe states insisted that it would be\ndemoralizing to their banking sys\ntems should national banks be per\nmitted to engage in such practice\n(while their own institutions were\ni prohibited. When federal authorities\n(fail to enforce the laws of Congress,\nJ the states asserted, the states may go\ninto the courts to have them enforc\ned, especially when such enforcement\n'ls considered by the states essential\n(to the preservation of the rights of\n(their citizens and the protection of\nI their personal and property rights.\n(The states insisted that as distinct\n|sovereignties they had the right to\nI protect their own sovereignty as well\njas the rights of their citizens\ni \u2019against the ravages of unlawful\nconduct\u201d alleged on the part of fed\neral officials.\nAdmitting the constitutionality of\nthe federal banking laws, and con\nceding that they could not prevent\n'the location of national banks within\nIthelr borders, the states insisted that\nthe national banks by their charters\n(were authorized to establish only one\n(banking institution.\nEach branch bank, such as that\nestablished by the St. Louis National\nj Bank, was a distinct banking unit,\nI the state- insisted, although it was\nconducted under direction of the offi-\nJ cers of the parent bank. They de-\nI dared that in practice there was no\n1 material differentiation between\nI branch banks, which Attorney Gen\neral Daugherty in an opinion bad\nheld unlawful, and branch offices,\nwhich lie had declared permissible.\nThey also recalled that George W.\nI Wlckersham while Attorney General\nhad held that national banka were\nnot authorized to conduct a banking\nbusiness except in the place desig\nnated in their certificates of organi\nzation, and tha\u2019t as late as 1920 the\ncontroller of currency had prohibited\nnational banks from establishing\nbranches, and in August, 1922, had\nstated that he had not authorized a\nnational bank to establish a branch\nIn states where state banks were not\npermitted to do -so.\nRights of Courts.\nThe St. Louis bank, supported by\nthe federal government, and the na\ntional\u2018banks which were permitted to\nparticipate in the case sought to\nmake the question of the jurisdiction\nof state courts in such matters the\nprincipal issue in their attack upon\nthe decision of the Missouri courts\nprohibiting the St. Louis institution\nfrom establishing a branch. National\nTips for Taxpayers\n.Vo. 25.\nHeavy penalties are, provided by\nthe revenue act for failure or\n\u201cwillful refusal\" to make a re- f\nqulred income tax return and pay\nthe tax on time \u2014on or before\nMarch 15, if the return is filed on\na calendar year basis. If the tax\npayer makes his return on the\nfiscal year basis it should be filed\non or before the 15th day of the i\nthird month following the close\nof the fiscal year.\nFor failure to file a return on\ntime a taxpayer becomes liable to\na penally of SI,OOO and a further\npenalty of 25 per cent of the\namount of the tax, unless the re\nturn is later filed and It Is satis- i\nfactorily shown to the commis\nsioner of Internal revenue that the\ndelinquency was due to a reason\nable cause, and not to willful\nneglect. For willful refusal to\nmake a return and pay the tax\non time a taxpayer beconfes liable\nto a penalty of SIO,OOO, or one\nyear\u2019s imprisonment, or both, to\ngether with the cost of prosecu\ntion and a penalty of 25 per cent\nof the amount of IhA tax.\nWhen a return is made in good\nfaith and an understatement of\nthe amount of the tax thereon is\ndue to no fault of the taxpayer,\nno penalty attaches, but interest\nattaches to the amount of the\ndeficiency at the rate of R per cent\na year. If the understatement is t\ndue to negligence\u2014\"absence of\nreasonable care under the circum- I\nstances\u201d \u2014there is to be added 5 j\nper cent of the total amount of\nthe deficiency, together with in- j\nterest on the amount of the de- J\nficiency at the rate of 12 per cent\na year from the time the tax was\ndue, or if paid on the installment\nbasis, on the deficiency of the in\nstallment from the time the in\nstallment was due. If the under\nstatement is fraudulent with in\ntent to evade the tax, the penalty\nis a fine of not more than SIO,OOO\nand imprisonment for not more\nthan one year, together with the\ncost of prosecution, and an added\nassessment of 50 per cent of the\namount of the deficiency.\nbanks, the creatures of the federal i\ngovernment, were subject, they as- j\nserted, exclusively to federal control\nin the administration of their bank\ning business. The states could not\nregulate the class of business such\nbanks could haniUe, they added, nor\nin any way regwate their adminis\ntrative affairs.\nThe rapid growth of city popula\ntion had resulted, the government\nsaid, in congestion of traffic in the\ndowntown districts, and in the de\nvelopment of residential sections at\nremote distances from the banks.\nTo accommodate distant customers j\nthe need is strongly felt in many lo- 1\ncalities. it added, for the banks to\nmaintain an office or offices at some\ndistance from their banking houses\nfor the purpose of receiving deposits\nand cashing checks. Branches for\nthat purpose could be lawfully estab\nlished, the government contended,\ndifferentiating, however, between\nsuch branches and those at which\nother business was transacted. If\nthe information with regard to the\nbusiness handled at tiie branch of Un-\nSt. Louis bank was correct, the gov\nernment stated, the class of business j\nit proposed to handle at the branch\nwas unlawful.\nDivided Control Danger.\nThe controller of the currency has\nthe supervisory power, the govern- I\nnient i xplained. to see that a national\nbanjv does not exceed its power in\ntransacting its \u201cusual business\u201d be\nyond the walls of its main office, de\nclaring that all \"usual business\"\nmust be transacted in the main of\nfice.\nThe whole national banking system\nwould be thrown into confusion, the\ngovernment insisted, should the fed\neral and state authorities have divided\ncontrol over it.\nThe growth of national banks can\nnot be restricted to the perpendicular,\nthe St. Louis bank contended. When\nconditions required expansion it was\nnot compelled to add an additional\nstory to its building, but could, it\ninsisted, locate in a building across\nthe street or several blocks distant.\nThat was held to be merely a matter\nof convenience and sound business\njudgment.\nAn impossible condition would b\ncreated, the national banks asserted,\nshould the highest court hold that\nthose stales which prohibit branch\nbanking had jurisdiction over na\ntional banks In such matters, and\ncould thereby prevent the establish\nment of branches, while national\nbanks located in states which had no\nsuch laws were free to establish\nbranches.\nlequitablel\n\nCo-Operative Building\nAssociation\nOrgnnir.rd ISTII\nI4t\u00bbi VKIH COMPLETED\nAssets *4,755,170.53\nSurplus ?1,54V120.!S\nAccomplishes Most\nSyslpmatio saving is Hie most\neffective mean* of aconnnilatlng\nmoney. Joint the Equitable ami save\nI wilh best results\nSubscription for the\n86th Issue of Stock\nlleing Received\nShares, $2.50 Per Month\nEQUITABLE BUILDING\n915 F St. N.W.\nJO HA JOY EDSOX. President\nFRANK I*. HUES IDE. Sec*y.\nFIRST MORTGAGES\nFOR SALE\nTHE TYPE OF SECURITY\nCONSERVATIVE IN\nVESTORS BUY\ni IN DENOMINATIONS TO\nSUIT PURCHASERS\nJAMES F. SHEA\nWe Buy and Sell\nLiberty Bonds\nTreasury Notes\nEtc.\nBond Department\nThe Washington Loan\nand Trust Company\n900 F Street\n620 17th Street\nContinental Trust Company\nCapital E\n5 One Million Dollar* E\nE 14tb H Street!\n|hililllilillllllilltUillllllllllllllllLHllil\u00a3\nFINANCIAL.\nFirst Mortgage Loans\nLoweat Rate* of Intenat and Commtaaioa.\nPrompt Action\nThomas J. Fisher Company, Inc.\n738 16th Street\nMoney to Loan\nSecured by flrat deed of trust on real eatata\nPrevailing Interest and commission.\nJoseph I. Weller\nk k Washington\u2019s OLDEST National Bank\nBefore the Treasury\nBuilding Was Erected\ni I 1 r The Metropolitan began serving the\nliilK KM Public many, years before the present\nI f\u25ba: I L U. S. Treasurv edifice was built.\nr A onncction with the OLDEST Xa\n-3 lt 1 hemal Bank in the District of Columbia\njd tag a B lves business prestige a* well as that\nmil lit fin Satisfaction arising from permanency.\nexperienced management and time-tried\nOrganized In 1814 policies.\nOur Savings Dept. Fags 3% Coni pound Interest\nMational Metropolitan Bank\nCapital, Surplus Undivided Profits Over $1,700,000\n15th St., Opposite U. S. Treasury\u2014llo Years Old\nDean, Onativia Co.\nStock Exchange Building\nNew Yor